{"key":"processedPost-8709666","value":{"id":8709666,"first":8709576,"last":8709849,"when":1217561919,"utime":"08/01/08 06:38 AM","content":"Actually, if you remove the jars from the kettle or PC, they only need a couple of hours in room temp air to cool down enough to inoculate.&nbsp; When the jars are only gently warm, it's ok to inoculate.&nbsp; Two to three hours is plenty.<br /><br />It's a myth that the inside of the jars are still hot when the outside cools.&nbsp; Cakes have too much water in them to hold much of a temperature differential.&nbsp; Besides, you inoculate against the glass anyway.<br />RR","title":"Re: another jar cooling method idea","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}